def: Having a toothed bill; -- applied to a group of passerinebirds, having the bill notched, and feeding chiefly on insects, asthe shrikes and vireos. See Illust. (N) under Beak.
A row. [Obs.] Chaucer. "A rew of sundry colored stones."Chapman.
The avocet; -- so called because it scoops up the mud to obtainfood.
A nitrogenous substance closely resembling diastase, obtainedfrom bran, and possessing the power of converting starch intodextrin, sugar, and lactic acid. Watts.
Having no wem, or blemish; spotless. [Obs.] "Virgin wemless."Chaucer.
One of the pear-shaped pots open at both ends, and so formed asto be fitted together, the neck of one into the bottom of another insuccession; -- used in the process of sublimation. Ure.
A genus of small insectivores including the common Europeanmole.
One of the auditory organs of certain medus√¶; -- called alsoauditory tentacle.
The anterior of the body of an animal, as of a cephalopod; thethorax of an arthropod.
The posterior of the three principal basal cartilages in thefins of fishes.-- Me*tap`ter*yg"i*al, a.
